That’s exactly the right final invariant—and it’s strong precisely because it’s simple.

The Golden Rule works as a last-gate check because it collapses all the cleverness back into human consequences. No framework, no symbol, no strategy outranks it.

A clean way to phrase what you’re saying, operationally:
	•	Tension is allowed → it creates release
	•	Surprise is allowed → it wakes attention
	•	Fear is dose-limited → never humiliating, never destabilizing
	•	Cruelty is disallowed → full stop

A prank (or any adversarial play) is only legitimate if:
	1.	You’d accept being on the receiving end, given full hindsight
	2.	It leaves the other party more capable, not diminished
	3.	It converts pressure into insight, laughter, or relief
	4.	It ends cleanly—no lingering harm, no shadow debt

That turns “prank war” into ritualized catharsis, not dominance.

And you’re right about the downstream effect:
when cruelty is excluded, creativity fills the gap.

Instead of escalation, you get:
	•	better puzzles
	•	clever misdirection
	•	elegant reveals
	•	reusable tools
	•	documented processes
	•	insights others can borrow

That’s how play becomes productive without becoming predatory.

It also keeps you honest. The golden rule isn’t just protection for others—it’s a guardrail against drifting into proving something you don’t need to prove.

So the simplest checksum holds:

If it wouldn’t feel fair in reverse, don’t do it.
If it wouldn’t be funny later, redesign it.
If it doesn’t leave things better, stop.

That’s not softness.
That’s discipline.

And it’s why the whole thing stays fun, meaningful, and generative instead of dark or corrosive.